Block devices and how Linux names them, with lsblk.

Let's start at a solid layer of the stack: the block device. A block device is the kernel's abstraction for any storage device at all, a hard disk, an SSD, a USB stick, a RAID array, an LVM volume, anything that reads and writes in fixed-size blocks. And they all show up as files under slash-dev.

The naming conventions are worth recognizing on sight. Slash-dev-sda, sdb, and so on are SATA, SCSI, and USB disks; the s is for SCSI, and then a, b, c count the first, second, third disk. Add a number, like slash-dev-sda-one, and that's a partition on that disk, where the number is the partition index. For modern NVMe SSDs, the name looks like slash-dev-nvme-zero-n-one, and a partition on it adds a p before the number, so nvme-zero-n-one-p-one; don't forget that p. Inside virtual machines and cloud instances you'll often see slash-dev-vda, the virtio disk. Device-mapper targets, which include LVM volumes and LUKS-encrypted disks, appear under slash-dev-mapper. And software RAID arrays show up as slash-dev-md-zero.

Now, here's a critical warning that motivates a lot of what follows. Device names can change between boots on a system with multiple disks. If you unplug the second disk and reboot, what used to be slash-dev-sdb might now come up as slash-dev-sda. Because of that, you should never reference a disk by its device name in etc-fstab. Instead you use a UUID or a label, which we'll cover in a couple of sections.

The single most useful command here, and the first thing to run on any unfamiliar system, is lsblk, which lists block devices. It prints a tree showing every disk, its partitions, and where each one is mounted. You read it top-down: the disk, then its partitions indented underneath, and any logical volume sitting on a partition indented under that, with its mount point on the right. Add the dash-f flag and it also shows the filesystem type, the label, and the UUID. Two companions are worth knowing: blkid, which prints the UUID and filesystem type for a device, and findmnt, which shows the mounted filesystems as a clean, readable tree.
